<paragraph id="8BC236D91C54A35DFF05A1B5ADD58E4E" blockId="9.[151,684,1520,1669]" lastBlockId="9.[714,1247,170,289]" pageId="9" pageNumber="76">
<taxonomicName id="4C7D4D5A1C54A35DFF05A1B5A83E8966" box="[177,349,1520,1545]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Celastraceae" genus="Brexia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Celastrales" pageId="9" pageNumber="76" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="coursiana">
<emphasis id="B909EACB1C54A35DFF05A1B5A83E8966" box="[177,349,1520,1545]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="76">Brexia coursiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a sparsely branched shrub to treelet in mid-elevation subhumid forest from the region of Zahamena PN/RNI (Fig. 5). It can be recognized by its leaves with an acute apex, inflorescences usually borne on the main stem (cauli- flory), slender peduncles less than 
<quantity id="4C859B3C1C54A35DFBE6A4EEADF68FAB" box="[1106,1173,170,197]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="76" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
broad with secondary axes branching well below the apex, a distinctly 5-lobed calyx, and petaloid disc segments with an irregularly laciniate margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC236D91C54A35DFD50A500ADD88EB6" blockId="9.[714,1247,324,473]" pageId="9" pageNumber="76">
